  35 |     - x0 = min-max normalized measurement time coordinate
  36 |     - x1 = varying experimental parameter extracted from column headers;
  37 |       sequential index if non-numeric, then min-max normalized
  38 |     - x2 = current normalized concentration/state c supplied by ODE integration
  39 |     - y  = response/concentration min-max normalized globally across the
  40 |       whole fit.tsv response table
  41 | 
  42 |     Many source files are already response-rescaled to 0→1. The evaluator uses
  43 |     the same global per-dataset min-max normalization, so those files remain on
  44 |     the same scale while unnormalized files are brought to the same range.
  45 | 
  46 |     Splits are trajectory-preserving rather than random point splits:
  47 |     - datasets with 3 or more parameter curves hold out whole x1 curves for
  48 |       validation;
  49 |     - datasets with fewer than 3 parameter curves use late-time validation
  50 |       segments, with the last training point included as the ODE handoff state.
  51 | 
  52 |     **Key constraint:** The ODE structure must be identical across all
  53 |     datasets, but a separate set of constants is fitted independently for each
  54 |     dataset. This means the RHS should capture reusable kinetic structure while
  55 |     fitted constants adapt to each dataset.
  56 | 
  57 |     **Hard single-equation rule:** Your EVOLVE-BLOCK must build exactly one
  58 |     symbolic ODE RHS template and submit it exactly once via
  59 |     `evaluate_expression(...)` from inside `evaluate_symbolic_candidate()`.
  60 |     Do not try several equations, several template families, fallback equations,
  61 |     helper functions that call the scorer repeatedly, multiple initial-value
  62 |     sweeps, or "best-of" selection logic. That is reward hacking for this task.
  63 |     The evaluator will reject these programs with combined_score = 0 and return
  64 |     a "Single-equation violation" error so you can correct it. You may use
  65 |     intermediate subexpressions like `rate`, `plateau`, and `growth`, but there
  66 |     must be one final RHS `expression` and one scorer call.
  67 |     Return the dictionary from that single `evaluate_expression(...)` call
  68 |     directly and unchanged. Do not edit, wrap, replace, or fabricate metrics.
  69 |     The evaluator statically checks your source before importing it: the
  70 |     function must be straight-line code and must directly end with
  71 |     `return evaluate_expression(...)`.
  72 | 
  73 |     ## Objective
  74 |     Improve mean validation NMSE across all datasets while keeping the symbolic
  75 |     differential equation compact. Higher `combined_score` means lower mean
  76 |     validation NMSE after integrating the ODE with `scipy.integrate.odeint`.
  77 |     Target smoothing is applied curve-wise in time order. Validation errors are
  78 |     normalized by the full train+validation response variance for that dataset,
  79 |     not by the often-flat held-out segment alone.
  80 | 
  81 |     Each dataset contributes one capped normalized loss to the reward so all
  82 |     protein datasets have roughly comparable influence:
  83 | 
  84 |         per_dataset_loss = min(dataset_nmse, 10.0)
  85 |         scored_nmse = mean(per_dataset_loss)
  86 | 
  87 |     Hard-case datasets are still reported in evaluator feedback so you can
  88 |     target outliers, but by default they do not receive extra reward weight.
  89 |     Higher `combined_score` then applies a bounded 20% parsimony penalty for
  90 |     more complex expressions:
  91 | 
  92 |         fit_score = 1 / (1 + scored_nmse)
  93 |         combined_score = fit_score * parsimony_penalty_factor
  94 | 
  95 |     A candidate that fails on any dataset is penalized heavily, so robustness
  96 |     across all datasets matters more than a strong fit on a subset. Simplicity
  97 |     is a secondary objective: do not sacrifice a meaningful fit improvement for
  98 |     a tiny reduction in complexity, but prefer the simpler expression when two
  99 |     candidates are close.
 100 | 
 101 |     Keep the equation structure as simple as possible. We do not want to overfit to the data. We want to find a general equation that works for all datasets. It is not preferable to come up with a very complex equation. We want a general governing law
 102 | 
 103 |     ## Focused agentic workflow
 104 |     Keep exploration short and bounded. You already know the benchmark layout,
 105 |     evaluator contract, and `pysr_harness` API from this prompt; do not spend
 106 |     many turns rediscovering them.
 107 | 
 108 |     Use tools when they provide information that materially improves the next
 109 |     candidate. Keep exploration purposeful and bounded: prefer targeted reads,
 110 |     searches, or paper lookups over broad discovery.
 111 | 
 112 |     Internet and paper tools are available and valuable for this task. When the
 113 |     run history shows stalled progress, repeated regressions, or uncertainty
 114 |     about the right structure, do not simply remix the current expression.
 115 |     Perform targeted research into governing relationships, empirical response
 116 |     shapes, scaling behavior, or robustness principles that may apply to this
 117 |     kind of data. Avoid copying a named formula blindly; extract the structural
 118 |     principle that makes it useful, then express that principle as one compact,
 119 |     stable symbolic template.
 120 | 
 121 |     If recent run history or traces show no external research yet, make at
 122 |     least one targeted `web_search` or `research_papers` call before finalizing
 123 |     your next candidate. If the tool returns no useful results or fails, say so
 124 |     briefly in your reasoning and continue from local evidence.
 125 | 
 126 |     Before every `run_command`, silently do this checklist:
 127 |     - Expected runtime under 10 seconds?
 128 |     - Expected output under 80 lines?
 129 |     - Uses only a known path from the prompt/repo map?
 130 |     - Avoids shell-only syntax?
 131 |     If any answer is "no", do not run the command.
 132 | 
 133 |     Never run filesystem discovery commands (`find`, broad `ls`, recursive
 134 |     scans, `/`, `/home`, `/usr`, `/opt`, or whole-repo searches). Never use
 135 |     shell metacharacters in safe-mode commands: no pipes (`|`), redirects
 136 |     (`>`, `2>/dev/null`), command chaining (`&&`, `;`), globs intended for the
 137 |     shell, or `head`/`tail` pipelines. Use only short Python snippets over known
 138 |     files, with explicit bounded printing.
 139 | 
 140 |     Do not dump full source files, full dataset listings, long per-dataset
 141 |     tables, or warning-heavy experiment transcripts into the conversation. If
 142 |     you test a model, test at most 3 representative datasets and print only one
 143 |     aggregate score plus at most 3 hard-case lines.
 144 | 
 145 |     If `read_file` says a path is outside the codebase root, do not spend more
 146 |     tool calls trying to rediscover that file. Use the API description in this
 147 |     prompt and output a complete candidate. Failed exploration is a signal to
 148 |     stop exploring, not to search more broadly.
 149 | 
 150 |     Stop exploring once you have a plausible, well-justified improvement.
 151 |     Output the complete improved EVOLVE-BLOCK program instead of running many
 152 |     variants. Repeated local experiments are worse than a concise, robust
 153 |     candidate.
 154 | 
 155 |     ## Optional Run History
 156 |     The AdaEvolve prompt may include a live run-progress section showing the
 157 |     current iteration, the requested run window, and remaining iterations. Use
 158 |     that progress signal to decide whether to exploit a promising direction or
 159 |     explore a different structure before the run budget is exhausted.
 160 | 
 161 |     If a visible run-history snapshot exists, you may inspect it to avoid
 162 |     repeating recently tried ideas. Use only the bounded files you need:
 163 |     - `reference/current_adaevolve_run/run_history_summary.json`
 164 |     - `reference/current_adaevolve_run/adaevolve_iteration_stats.jsonl`
 165 |     - `reference/current_adaevolve_run/checkpoints/`
 166 |     - `reference/agentic_trace_*.json`
 167 | 
 168 |     Treat this snapshot as context, not as a target to copy. Prefer the summary
 169 |     first; only read individual checkpoint programs when you need to understand
 170 |     a specific prior candidate. Use recent agentic traces only when you need to
 171 |     understand which tool calls, research paths, or reasoning steps led to the
 172 |     previous candidate.
 173 | 
 174 |     When reading iteration stats, distinguish the fields carefully:
 175 |     - `global.global_best_score` is the best score found up to and including
 176 |       that iteration.
 177 |     - `global.current_iteration_best_score` is the best score among programs
 178 |       produced in that specific iteration.
 179 |     - `iteration_result.child_program.metrics.combined_score` is the score of
 180 |       the newly generated child for that iteration.
 181 |     - A plateau means the child scores are failing to exceed the running best
 182 |       for several iterations, even if `global_best_score` remains high.
 183 | 
 184 |     ## Task
 185 |     Improve the `evaluate_symbolic_candidate()` function in the EVOLVE-BLOCK.
 186 |     Build an explicit symbolic ODE RHS template using the `pysr_harness` API.
 187 |     The evaluator interprets your submitted expression as:
 188 | 
 189 |         d(c)/dt = expression
 190 | 
 191 |     Use `pysr_harness.equation_session` helpers:
 192 |     - `feature_symbols(n)` → PySR variables `x0`, `x1`, ...
 193 |       Here x0 is time t, x1 is the experimental parameter, and x2 is the
 194 |       current concentration/state c.
 195 |     - `constant_symbols(n)` → tunable constants `c0`, `c1`, ...
 196 |     - `evaluate_expression(expr, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, constants=...)`
 197 |       fits constants via least-squares, integrates `dc/dt = expr` with
 198 |       `scipy.integrate.odeint` using the known initial concentration values on
 199 |       the relevant split, and returns scored metrics. The evaluator performs a
 200 |       small fixed multi-start over scaled versions of your supplied
 201 |       `initial_values`, so do not implement initializer sweeps in the candidate.
 202 | 
 203 |     ## Search Strategy
 204 |     Do not assume a particular equation family. Use the current candidate,
 205 |     prior scores, evaluator feedback, and any bounded diagnostics you choose
 206 |     to inspect to infer what structural change is justified.
 207 | 
 208 |     Understand exploration vs exploitation in this evolutionary search:
 209 |     - Exploration means deliberately moving to a different structural region
 210 |       when local mutations are not improving the running best. Use it to test
 211 |       a new principle, transformation, variable interaction, or stability idea.
 212 |       Exploration should still be disciplined: explain what failure mode or
 213 |       hypothesis the new structure targets.
 214 |     - Exploitation means refining a promising family after it shows improvement.
 215 |       Use it for small, controlled changes that preserve the useful behavior
 216 |       while addressing a clear limitation such as scaling, baseline behavior,
 217 |       numerical conditioning, or unnecessary complexity.
 218 |     - If recent child scores regress or duplicate the current best, switch from
 219 |       incremental tweaks to evidence gathering. Inspect run history, hard cases,
 220 |       and, when useful, external sources before proposing the next expression.
 221 |     - If a child improves substantially, exploit that direction with minimal
 222 |       changes rather than immediately replacing the whole structure.
 223 | 
 224 |     Before changing the expression, identify the most likely limitation:
 225 |     - poor fit quality on many datasets
 226 |     - non-finite predictions or invalid arithmetic on one or more datasets
 227 |     - excessive sensitivity to x0 or x1 scaling
 228 |     - over-parameterization that makes constant fitting unreliable
 229 |     - under-parameterization that cannot capture shared structure
 230 |     - a redundant term that adds complexity without improving robustness
 231 | 
 232 |     Prefer the smallest structural change that targets the limitation you
 233 |     identify. Do not add complexity merely because more constants are allowed.
 234 |     Because complexity has a small direct score penalty, every extra operation
 235 |     or fitted constant should have a clear expected payoff in validation fit or
 236 |     robustness.
 237 | 
 238 |     Good candidates are:
 239 |     - smooth and globally defined over the observed x0 and x1 ranges
 240 |     - numerically stable during least-squares fitting
 241 |     - compact enough for reliable optimization from one initial point
 242 |     - able to use x1 when it is informative without depending on it too strongly
 243 |     - robust on small, noisy, or unusually scaled datasets
 244 | 
 245 |     Be especially cautious with operations that can create singularities,
 246 |     non-real values, overflow, or invalid powers during fitting. If you use
 247 |     division, exponentials, logarithms, square roots, or variable exponents,
 248 |     explain why the resulting expression remains well behaved.
 249 | 
 250 |     Keep the number of fitted constants moderate. Too many constants risk
 251 |     unstable fits on small datasets; too few can underfit shared structure.
 252 | 
 253 |     ## Constraints
 254 |     - Exactly one call to `evaluate_expression(...)` per
 255 |       `evaluate_symbolic_candidate()` invocation.
 256 |     - Directly `return evaluate_expression(...)`; do not assign the result to a
 257 |       variable, edit it, wrap it, or post-process it.
 258 |     - The `equation_template` returned by the scorer must be identical for every
 259 |       dataset; only fitted constant values may differ across datasets.
 260 |     - Keep `evaluate_symbolic_candidate()` straight-line: no loops, conditionals,
 261 |       try/except blocks, nested functions/classes, comprehensions, helper
 262 |       function calls, or imports inside the function.
 263 |     - Do not use `Piecewise`, `Max`, `Min`, `sign`, `floor`, `ceiling`,
 264 |       `Heaviside`, relational/boolean expressions, or other gated/conditional
 265 |       symbolic constructs.
 266 |     - Keep symbolic complexity under 160 nodes and fitted constants under 13.
 267 |     - Do NOT call PySRRegressor.fit, run_gp_session, or equation_search.
 268 |     - Do NOT implement multiple candidate templates and choose the one with the
 269 |       lowest loss.
 270 |     - Keep expressions numerically stable and general.
 271 |     - Do not hardcode data values or indices.
 272 |     - Keep runtime reasonable (3000s timeout for all datasets combined).
